<p>Buying a boat is the easy part. The purchase price — whether it's £15,000 for a well-used 28-footer or £250,000 for a 40ft cruiser-racer — is a one-time event. What catches most new owners off guard is the relentless, cumulative cost of keeping that boat in the water, maintained, insured, and ready to sail. The old joke about a boat being "a hole in the water into which you pour money" exists for a reason, but the reality is more nuanced than the joke suggests. Most of these costs are predictable, manageable, and — if you're smart about it — reducible.</p>

<h2>Marina Berthing</h2>

<p>This is typically the single largest annual cost. In South Devon, berth fees vary significantly by marina and vessel size:</p>

<p><strong>Brixham Marina (MDL):</strong> Annual berth fees range from approximately £3,500-4,200 for a 10-metre vessel to £7,000-9,000+ for boats approaching 18 metres. Brixham tends to be slightly cheaper than Torquay, reflecting the tidal access constraints.</p>

<p><strong>Torquay Marina (MDL):</strong> Premium pricing for a premium facility. Expect approximately £4,200-5,500 for 10 metres, rising to £10,000-14,000+ for larger vessels approaching 30 metres. The 5 Gold Anchor rating and 24/7 access command a premium.</p>

<p><strong>Dartmouth (Darthaven Marina):</strong> Mid-range pricing for marina berths, though Dart Harbour swing moorings offer a substantially cheaper alternative at roughly £2,000-4,000 per year depending on size and location. The trade-off is exposure to the river's estuarine conditions and the inconvenience of tender access.</p>

<h2>Insurance</h2>

<p>Marine insurance costs depend heavily on the vessel's value, age, intended cruising area, and the owner's experience. For a typical 10-15 metre sailing yacht valued at £40,000-120,000, expect annual premiums of approximately £600-1,500 for comprehensive cover including third-party liability. Motor vessels generally attract slightly higher premiums due to their higher replacement values and engine-related risks.</p>

<p>One factor many owners overlook: insurers increasingly ask about hull maintenance records when assessing claims. A documented cleaning and inspection history demonstrates good maintenance practice — and our HD video reports provide exactly this kind of timestamped evidence.</p>

<h2>Annual Maintenance</h2>

<p>This is where costs become highly variable and where informed owners can save meaningful money through good planning:</p>

<p><strong>Antifouling:</strong> A full antifouling application for a 12-metre yacht costs approximately £800-1,500 including haul-out, paint, and labour. Most owners repaint annually or biannually. Extending your antifouling life by even one season through regular professional cleaning saves a significant sum — and our quarterly cleaning service costs less annually than a single repaint.</p>

<p><strong>Engine servicing:</strong> Annual engine service for a marine diesel costs approximately £300-600 depending on engine type and whether it's a DIY or professional job. Impeller changes, oil and filter replacement, and antifreeze renewal are standard annual items.</p>

<p><strong>Rigging (sailing yachts):</strong> Standing rigging should be inspected annually and replaced every 10-15 years. A full re-rig on a 12-metre yacht costs £3,000-6,000. Running rigging — halyards, sheets, control lines — wears with use and typically needs partial replacement every 3-5 years.</p>

<p><strong>Electronics:</strong> Marine electronics have a finite lifespan, and the marine environment is unkind to sensitive equipment. Budget for occasional chart plotter, VHF, AIS, and instrument replacement — individually these are £200-1,500+ items, and they tend to fail at inconvenient moments.</p>

<p><strong>Hull cleaning:</strong> At our standard rate of £15 per metre, four quarterly cleans on a 12-metre yacht cost £720 per year. On an Essential plan, that drops to £612. This is a modest cost relative to the fuel savings, antifouling preservation, and performance benefits it delivers — and arguably the best-value maintenance investment you can make on any boat.</p>

<h2>The Costs Nobody Warns You About</h2>

<p>Beyond the predictable expenses, boat ownership in South Devon comes with a few costs that catch newcomers off guard:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Tender and dinghy:</strong> If you're on a swing mooring in Dartmouth, you need a tender to reach your boat. A reasonable inflatable with an outboard costs £1,500-3,000, plus annual servicing, fuel, and somewhere to store it.</li>
  <li><strong>Safety equipment renewal:</strong> Liferaft servicing (annual, £200-400), flare replacement (every 3 years, £150-250), fire extinguisher servicing, EPIRB battery renewal — these are mandatory costs that add up quietly.</li>
  <li><strong>Parking:</strong> Marina car parking in Brixham and Torquay is paid and often limited. If you visit your boat weekly, the annual parking cost alone can reach £500-800.</li>
  <li><strong>The "while you're at it" factor:</strong> Every haul-out reveals something else that needs attention. A skin fitting that's weeping. A keel bolt that looks corroded. A patch of gelcoat crazing that wasn't visible from the waterline. Each discovery adds cost to what you thought was a routine lift-out.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Annual Total</h2>

<p>For a 12-metre sailing yacht on a Brixham annual berth, the realistic all-in annual cost of ownership looks roughly like this: berthing £4,000 + insurance £800 + antifouling £1,200 (biannual, amortised) + engine service £400 + hull cleaning plan £612 + safety equipment £300 + miscellaneous maintenance £500-1,000. That puts you at approximately £7,800-8,300 per year — before you've bought a single shackle, replaced a halyard, or filled the diesel tank.</p>

<p>Is it worth it? That's a question only you can answer. But for the boat owners who sail out of Brixham, Torquay, and Dartmouth every weekend, who watch the sun set over Torbay from their cockpit, and who wouldn't trade their mooring for a house extension — the answer is invariably yes.</p>

